node.text: @david.a.cromer you have to look at the reasons why you do the things you do. If you had free will you could choose to believe in unicorns, and you’d really believe it. You’d choose to stick to a diet and never falter your whole life. You’d choose your core values randomly. But we don’t do that. We are a system of complex inputs. We don’t choose our core values or what we desire, they choose us. You couldn’t choose to believe a god you don’t believe in, or choose to value something you don’t.

@papayaqueen79 yes as parents we don’t just shame a toddler for a tantrum that they can’t fully control. We give resources, and discipline, to curb behavior in another direction. We can still choose to jail people, even with some compassion that they were dealt a bad hand in life.
#freewill #nononsensespirituality

@david.a.cromer it’s an argument based mostly in physics… I also find it a little “missing forest for the trees” but it’s not as simple as you’d think. Tho I personally find “no free will” to be reductionist, it’s not necessarily UNtrue

@david.a.cromer also when you desire to have something that is not a system of input. What does one benefit from desire if all one needs is basic things for survival? One does not need desires if you just need food, clothing and shelter. Typically, the animal kingdom doesn't have desires on the functionality to survive based on instinct to survive. This is a very very difficult and debatable topic. I personally disagree but everyone is entitled to their beliefs whether I agree or not.

@david.a.cromer you have to look at the reasons why you do the things you do. If you had free will you could choose to believe in unicorns, and you’d really believe it. You’d choose to stick to a diet and never falter your whole life. You’d choose your core values randomly. But we don’t do that. We are a system of complex inputs. We don’t choose our core values or what we desire, they choose us. You couldn’t choose to believe a god you don’t believe in, or choose to value something you don’t.
I don’t understand. You could have decided, at any point, to go the gym, but instead you chose other things. That is free will. What am I missing?
@real_rebeccabex no, because I didn’t choose that my moms health inspired me. I didn’t choose any of my core values or desires.

@nononsensespirituality but you can ... we are better off choosing values that we believe are best for us and the citizen body and "liking" those than just compulsively going along with values that happened to be formed in our comfort configurations by circumstance. Philosophy allows us to imagine the person and world we want and act in accordance consciously to being them about.

@thecitizenbody no one chooses their core values. You “choose” them based on what already resonates with you. You naturally are inclined to justice over mercy, or vice versa. These are not random choices. The core values choose you in a way, and are formed as you walk out the door and have to create a hierarchy of values. I’m not saying we take our core values from society giving them to you. It’s far deeper than that. Even the disposition to study philosophy is found in some and not in others, by no real choice of their own.

Can’t your desires and choice to change inputs be at least partially free will? As in, you see your mother being healthy and desire the same results, therefore you choose to work towards that goal. Even if some aspects of life is beyond our control we aren’t incapable of affecting or changing our lives and the results, in my own opinion ofc. 🤔

@papayaqueen79 But I find it very interesting that, since we have no free will, you'd think it wouldn't be correct to shame people for poor choices. However, it's the  potential shaming that, ironically, helps us make better decisions. Or sometimes it's the punishment.  So even though nobody can help how "bad" we are, we still need to believe it was their choice, so we will shame them, so they will make better choices.  If my logic is wrong here, please let me know because I'm not very intelligent. 😂 Not my fault though!

@papayaqueen79 yes as parents we don’t just shame a toddler for a tantrum that they can’t fully control. We give resources, and discipline, to curb behavior in another direction. We can still choose to jail people, even with some compassion that they were dealt a bad hand in life.

I think of determinism in human behavior as similar to a huge barrel of tiny balls that is poured out. None of us can predict exactly where each little ball will go. It's not possible. However, that doesn't mean it's random. It's all cause and effect.  And, btw, the meatsuit term makes me uncomfortable. 😂 But I suppose that's what we are.
@cozy.pigeontoes I do a full YouTube video on it that totally unpacks it if you like

You are correct, this meat suit here IS interested in this concept. However, there is something about this concept that I just do not get. I can’t comprehend it. I’ll ask my friend to help explain it to me.
Is free will and choice different? Because I think of them as the same, and you almost always have a choice - with lots of circumstances affecting that choice

“Working with the system that I am.”
I love that! It is a system of complex living things at play, but our ego thinks it’s a play about it. We are more bacteria than our own cells, kludged together from dead star stuff and evolution, a blip on the trillion trillion years cosmic lifespan.

🤔 Or how you feel is an influence on your will. Like, the creature that is you has a status of balances... if you're imbalanced, your will, will be heavier than it is on other days... is it a lack of will... or an awareness of your well being in relation to your will?
This is basically every convo with chatgpt

The system that is me..what inputs do I need…I did stop!!! I was compelled to b/c it was always going to happen..b/c I had a dad that was always curious about the world around him which in turn made me take on the habit of curiosity…
You have the free will to go to the gym or not go to the gym. Cause and effect of whether you go is irrelevant to the fact you had the free will to choose. And you did, to not go.
Made me think and laugh. Bravo👏
What do you say to someone when they are “conflicted” on what appears to be a free will choice. I can’t put my finger on why some things feel like core values and other things are not 100%.
Just make zucchini pancakes

Interesting philosophy. Not sure I track it all the way, but I don't have an opinion on free will one way or the other. It does seem that "you" have a very psychosomatic definition of "self" (what you're calling the "meat suit") I tend towards more Eastern/Chinese systems of philosophy, especially in terms of "spirituality".

Yep exactly. 
Taking that gym thought another step...
People dont have 'free will' to be an olympic level athlete.  Instead Olympians are born with random genetics which predetermine their ability to excel at specific events. 
A person cant simply use 'free will' to decide they're going to be a world class athlete.
I love the power of this soft and deep wisdom 🩷🔥💎

What are you even rambling about? If you don't have free will this video doesn't matter your opinion doesn't matter and how a person reacts to your video is also not within their power and so everything is meaningless. Shut the fuck up
@chrewtransformation I’ve heard that explained as you can want what you will but you can’t will what you will

@cosmicskeptic posted a video about freewill years ago that really helped me understand this concept. What he said that made it click was that we can't choose to not like something or to not want to do something we want to do or that we like.
